<|startoftext|>Question:I want to talk about an application for a federal debt relief grant..? What do I need?
Answer:In the federal statute, the Federal Government has authority to make all Federal obligations to people in the United States with federal debt discharge (including those with federal debt relief) contingent upon the debtor's compliance with the applicable repayment requirements.  In the United States, the debt discharge is based on the number of days since the debtor began repayment in the month before the debtor entered into the debt discharge.  The debtor (or his or her creditors) have the right to request the discharge when the debtor is first filing for Chapter 13 bankruptcy (the discharge procedure).  If the debt discharged by the debtor was made earlier, then the debtor is obligated to file for Chapter 13 bankruptcy (which has a discharge period during which each subsequent Chapter 13 bankruptcy may be terminated if both persons are deemed not to be eligible for a benefit).  

The debtor also has the right to request a discharge in an emergency.  

If you are unable to find someone to talk to on the telephone or e-mail about your situation, you should seek the assistance of an attorney with a professional opinion.  

In order for the debt to be discharged, the debtor must be either an individual who does not owe any current balances with his or her assets or a nonresident dependent (a dependent) (i.e. those who are also living abroad).  You can file for a discharge as long as the debt was paid in full and any outstanding judgments are paid by him or her within ten (10) days from date of discharge. 

Your attorney will also evaluate the debt to determine if it is in the best financial condition.  If that assessment is negative, you must file your bankruptcy to pay back any outstanding judgments owed (this is not in the debtor's best financial condition).

